<subSubSection id="2AC3655CFFA3244EFFCBF35F063B0519" pageId="10" pageNumber="295" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="626636D7FFA3244EFFCBF35F063B0519" blockId="10.[102,1310,3168,3485]" lastBlockId="10.[1375,2584,722,3475]" pageId="10" pageNumber="295">
<taxonomicName id="A5D94D54FFA3244EFFCBF35F0E130DAB" authorityName="Spencer" authorityYear="1896" box="[104,347,3246,3279]" class="Mammalia" family="Dasyuridae" genus="Phascogale" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dasyuromorphia" pageId="10" pageNumber="295" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="macdonnellensis">P. macdonnellensis</taxonomicName>
takes its specific name from the MacDonnell Ranges, near Alice Springs, where it was first collected in 1894 on the Horn Scientific Expedition to central Australia; it was described as Phascologale 
<taxonomicName id="A5D94D54FFA3244EFD7BF2F40CEB0C7A" authorityName="Spencer" authorityYear="1896" box="[728,931,3333,3358]" class="Mammalia" family="Dasyuridae" genus="Phascogale" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dasyuromorphia" pageId="10" pageNumber="295" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="macdonnellensis">macdonnellensis</taxonomicName>
by W. B. Spencer two years later. There are currently six recognized species of “false antechinuses:” 
<taxonomicName id="A5D94D54FFA3244EFBECF2D40BEB0C22" authorityName="Johnson" authorityYear="1954" box="[1103,1187,3365,3398]" class="Mammalia" family="Dasyuridae" genus="Antechinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dasyuromorphia" pageId="10" pageNumber="295" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="bilarni">bilarni</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="A5D94D54FFA3244EFB17F2D40F9B0C09" authorityName="Spencer" authorityYear="1896" class="Mammalia" family="Dasyuridae" genus="Phascogale" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dasyuromorphia" pageId="10" pageNumber="295" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="macdonnellensis">macdonnellensis</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="A5D94D54FFA3244EFF41F2A10E190C09" baseAuthorityName="Thomas" baseAuthorityYear="1906" box="[226,337,3408,3437]" class="Mammalia" family="Dasyuridae" genus="Pseudantechinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dasyuromorphia" pageId="10" pageNumber="295" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="mimulus">mimulus</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="A5D94D54FFA3244EFEFCF2A10E980C09" box="[351,464,3408,3437]" class="Mammalia" family="Dasyuridae" genus="Pseudantechinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dasyuromorphia" pageId="10" pageNumber="295" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="ningbing">ningbing</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="A5D94D54FFA3244EFE7CF2A10D500C09" authorityName="Cooper, Aplin &amp; Adams" authorityYear="2000" box="[479,536,3408,3437]" class="Mammalia" family="Dasyuridae" genus="Pseudantechinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dasyuromorphia" pageId="10" pageNumber="295" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="roryi">roryi</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName id="A5D94D54FFA3244EFDC0F2A10D9D0C09" authorityName="Kitchener &amp; Caputi" authorityYear="1988" box="[611,725,3408,3437]" class="Mammalia" family="Dasyuridae" genus="Pseudantechinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dasyuromorphia" pageId="10" pageNumber="295" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="woolleyae">woolleyae</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="A5D94D54FFA3244EFD40F2A10CE70C09" authorityName="Spencer" authorityYear="1896" box="[739,943,3408,3437]" class="Mammalia" family="Dasyuridae" genus="Phascogale" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dasyuromorphia" pageId="10" pageNumber="295" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="macdonnellensis">macdonnellensis</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName id="A5D94D54FFA3244EFC59F2A10B200C09" baseAuthorityName="Thomas" baseAuthorityYear="1906" box="[1018,1128,3408,3437]" class="Mammalia" family="Dasyuridae" genus="Pseudantechinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dasyuromorphia" pageId="10" pageNumber="295" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="mimulus">mimulus</taxonomicName>
were initially placed under 
<taxonomicName id="A5D94D54FFA3244EFE8EF28D0EF50CF1" box="[301,445,3452,3477]" class="Mammalia" family="Dasyuridae" genus="Antechinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dasyuromorphia" pageId="10" pageNumber="295" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Antechinus</taxonomicName>
, along with 
<taxonomicName id="A5D94D54FFA3244EFDC9F28D0CC40CF1" baseAuthorityName="Gray" baseAuthorityYear="1842" box="[618,908,3452,3477]" class="Mammalia" family="Dasyuridae" genus="Parantechinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dasyuromorphia" pageId="10" pageNumber="295" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="apicalis">Parantechinus apicalis</taxonomicName>
. Nevertheless, G. H. H. Tate in 1947 erected a new genus (
<taxonomicName id="A5D94D54FFA3244EF62AFED10750000C" authorityName="Tate" authorityYear="1947" class="Mammalia" family="Dasyuridae" genus="Pseudantechinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dasyuromorphia" pageId="10" pageNumber="295" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Pseudantechinus</taxonomicName>
) for the false antechinuses, 
<taxonomicName id="A5D94D54FFA3244EF678FEBA071500F4" authorityName="Spencer" authorityYear="1896" class="Mammalia" family="Dasyuridae" genus="Phascogale" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dasyuromorphia" pageId="10" pageNumber="295" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="macdonnellensis">macdonnellensis</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="A5D94D54FFA3244EF71DFE86066500F4" baseAuthorityName="Thomas" baseAuthorityYear="1906" box="[2238,2349,375,400]" class="Mammalia" family="Dasyuridae" genus="Pseudantechinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dasyuromorphia" pageId="10" pageNumber="295" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="mimulus">mimulus</taxonomicName>
, and a monotypic genus for 
<taxonomicName id="A5D94D54FFA3244EF707FE67064B00D3" baseAuthorityName="Gray" baseAuthorityYear="1842" box="[2212,2307,406,439]" class="Mammalia" family="Dasyuridae" genus="Parantechinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dasyuromorphia" pageId="10" pageNumber="295" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="apicalis">apicalis</taxonomicName>
(
<taxonomicName id="A5D94D54FFA3244EF6B9FE67069100D3" box="[2330,2521,406,439]" class="Mammalia" family="Dasyuridae" genus="Parantechinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dasyuromorphia" pageId="10" pageNumber="295" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Parantechinus</taxonomicName>
). In 1964, W. D. L. Ride, doubting the validity of Tate’s new genera, returned all three species to 
<taxonomicName id="A5D94D54FFA3244EF7FAFDFD07A20349" box="[2137,2282,524,557]" class="Mammalia" family="Dasyuridae" genus="Antechinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dasyuromorphia" pageId="10" pageNumber="295" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Antechinus</taxonomicName>
. Later, P. A. Woolley examined penile morphology of Ride’s 
<taxonomicName id="A5D94D54FFA3244EF860FDAA071B0318" box="[1987,2131,603,636]" class="Mammalia" family="Dasyuridae" genus="Antechinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dasyuromorphia" pageId="10" pageNumber="295" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Antechinus</taxonomicName>
supergroup and proposed that 
<taxonomicName id="A5D94D54FFA3244EF866FD7707D903C7" authorityName="Spencer" authorityYear="1896" box="[1989,2193,646,675]" class="Mammalia" family="Dasyuridae" genus="Phascogale" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dasyuromorphia" pageId="10" pageNumber="295" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="macdonnellensis">macdonnellensis</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="A5D94D54FFA3244EF713FD77064C03C7" authorityName="Johnson" authorityYear="1954" box="[2224,2308,646,675]" class="Mammalia" family="Dasyuridae" genus="Antechinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dasyuromorphia" pageId="10" pageNumber="295" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="bilarni">bilarni</taxonomicName>
, the undescribed “ 
<taxonomicName id="A5D94D54FFA3244EF872FD5B070C03AF" box="[2001,2116,682,715]" class="Mammalia" family="Dasyuridae" genus="Pseudantechinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dasyuromorphia" pageId="10" pageNumber="295" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="ningbing">ningbing</taxonomicName>
,” and 
<taxonomicName id="A5D94D54FFA3244EF70FFD5B064403AF" baseAuthorityName="Gray" baseAuthorityYear="1842" box="[2220,2316,682,715]" class="Mammalia" family="Dasyuridae" genus="Parantechinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dasyuromorphia" pageId="10" pageNumber="295" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="apicalis">apicalis</taxonomicName>
formed a distinct group. M. Archer subsequently resurrected both of Tate’s genera, assigning 
<taxonomicName id="A5D94D54FFA3244EF60FFD230A81027F" authorityName="Spencer" authorityYear="1896" class="Mammalia" family="Dasyuridae" genus="Phascogale" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dasyuromorphia" pageId="10" pageNumber="295" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="macdonnellensis">macdonnellensis</taxonomicName>
and “ 
<taxonomicName id="A5D94D54FFA3244EF982FCF309DD027F" box="[1569,1685,770,795]" class="Mammalia" family="Dasyuridae" genus="Pseudantechinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dasyuromorphia" pageId="10" pageNumber="295" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="ningbing">ningbing</taxonomicName>
” to 
<taxonomicName id="A5D94D54FFA3244EF976FCF308E3027F" authorityName="Tate" authorityYear="1947" box="[1749,1963,770,795]" class="Mammalia" family="Dasyuridae" genus="Pseudantechinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dasyuromorphia" pageId="10" pageNumber="295" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Pseudantechinus</taxonomicName>
, and both 
<taxonomicName id="A5D94D54FFA3244EF7ECFCF307EC027F" authorityName="Johnson" authorityYear="1954" box="[2127,2212,770,795]" class="Mammalia" family="Dasyuridae" genus="Antechinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dasyuromorphia" pageId="10" pageNumber="295" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="bilarni">bilarni</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="A5D94D54FFA3244EF751FCF30619027F" baseAuthorityName="Gray" baseAuthorityYear="1842" box="[2290,2385,770,795]" class="Mammalia" family="Dasyuridae" genus="Parantechinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dasyuromorphia" pageId="10" pageNumber="295" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="apicalis">apicalis</taxonomicName>
to 
<taxonomicName id="A5D94D54FFA3244EF626FCF30AD80226" class="Mammalia" family="Dasyuridae" genus="Parantechinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dasyuromorphia" pageId="10" pageNumber="295" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Parantechinus</taxonomicName>
. Genetic work on 
<taxonomicName id="A5D94D54FFA3244EF908FCD008C80226" authorityName="Tate" authorityYear="1947" box="[1707,1920,801,834]" class="Mammalia" family="Dasyuridae" genus="Pseudantechinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dasyuromorphia" pageId="10" pageNumber="295" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Pseudantechinus</taxonomicName>
has paralleled morphological research since P. R. Baverstock and colleagues used allozymes to confirm Tate’s contended genera 
<taxonomicName id="A5D94D54FFA3244EFAFCFC9E097C02F4" authorityName="Tate" authorityYear="1947" box="[1375,1588,879,912]" class="Mammalia" family="Dasyuridae" genus="Pseudantechinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dasyuromorphia" pageId="10" pageNumber="295" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Pseudantechinus</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="A5D94D54FFA3244EF9DDFC9E087F02F4" box="[1662,1847,879,912]" class="Mammalia" family="Dasyuridae" genus="Parantechinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dasyuromorphia" pageId="10" pageNumber="295" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Parantechinus</taxonomicName>
. Direct sequencing of mtDNA and nDNA has been conducted over the last decade. Consensus of this work is: monotypic genera containing 
<taxonomicName id="A5D94D54FFA3244EFA34FC4F09F102BB" baseAuthorityName="Gray" baseAuthorityYear="1842" box="[1431,1721,958,991]" class="Mammalia" family="Dasyuridae" genus="Parantechinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dasyuromorphia" pageId="10" pageNumber="295" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="apicalis">Parantechinus apicalis</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="A5D94D54FFA3244EF8A1FC4F077C02BB" baseAuthorityName="Ride" baseAuthorityYear="1964" box="[1794,2100,958,991]" class="Mammalia" family="Dasyuridae" genus="Dasykaluta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dasyuromorphia" pageId="10" pageNumber="295" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="rosamondae">Dasykaluta rosamondae</taxonomicName>
are discrete from each other and from the genus 
<taxonomicName id="A5D94D54FFA3244EF999FC1708580563" authorityName="Tate" authorityYear="1947" box="[1594,1808,998,1031]" class="Mammalia" family="Dasyuridae" genus="Pseudantechinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dasyuromorphia" pageId="10" pageNumber="295" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Pseudantechinus</taxonomicName>
, P. bilarniis very different genetically from 
<taxonomicName id="A5D94D54FFA3244EF6FEFC170A88054A" baseAuthorityName="Gray" baseAuthorityYear="1842" class="Mammalia" family="Dasyuridae" genus="Parantechinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dasyuromorphia" pageId="10" pageNumber="295" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="apicalis">Parantechinus apicalis</taxonomicName>
and all other species of 
<taxonomicName id="A5D94D54FFA3244EF8B8FBFC08B9054A" authorityName="Tate" authorityYear="1947" box="[1819,2033,1037,1070]" class="Mammalia" family="Dasyuridae" genus="Pseudantechinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dasyuromorphia" pageId="10" pageNumber="295" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Pseudantechinus</taxonomicName>
; and 
<taxonomicName id="A5D94D54FFA3244EF7E3FBFC079A054A" baseAuthorityName="Thomas" baseAuthorityYear="1906" box="[2112,2258,1037,1070]" class="Mammalia" family="Dasyuridae" genus="Pseudantechinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dasyuromorphia" pageId="10" pageNumber="295" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="mimulus">P. mimulus</taxonomicName>
was recovered as sister to a clade containing 
<taxonomicName id="A5D94D54FFA3244EF931FBC408370532" authorityName="Spencer" authorityYear="1896" box="[1682,1919,1077,1110]" class="Mammalia" family="Dasyuridae" genus="Phascogale" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dasyuromorphia" pageId="10" pageNumber="295" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="macdonnellensis">P. macdonnellensis</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="A5D94D54FFA3244EF864FBC4076A0532" authorityName="Cooper, Aplin &amp; Adams" authorityYear="2000" box="[1991,2082,1077,1110]" class="Mammalia" family="Dasyuridae" genus="Pseudantechinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dasyuromorphia" pageId="10" pageNumber="208" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="roryi">P. roryi</taxonomicName>
, but the latter two species were not reciprocally monophyletic, raising questions about their status. Monotypic.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="2AC3655CFFA3244EFAFCFB7D07F705A8" pageId="10" pageNumber="295" type="distribution">
<caption id="36A6665FFFA3244EFAFCFB7D07F705A8" ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6608152" ID-Zenodo-Dep="6608152" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6608152/files/figure.png" inLine="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="295" targetBox="[1371,1963,298,712]" targetPageId="10">
<paragraph id="626636D7FFA3244EFAFCFB7D07F705A8" blockId="10.[1375,2584,722,3475]" pageId="10" pageNumber="295">
<emphasis id="50ADEAC5FFA3244EFAFCFB7D094705C1" bold="true" box="[1375,1551,1164,1189]" pageId="10" pageNumber="295">Distribution.</emphasis>
C Australia, including E Western Australia, C &amp; S Northern Territory, N South Australia, and an isolated locality in far W Queensland.
</paragraph>
</caption>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="2AC3655CFFA3244EFAFCFB2308EA076C" pageId="10" pageNumber="295" type="description">
<paragraph id="626636D7FFA3244EFAFCFB2308EA076C" blockId="10.[1375,2584,722,3475]" pageId="10" pageNumber="295">
<emphasis id="50ADEAC5FFA3244EFAFCFB2309130597" bold="true" box="[1375,1627,1234,1267]" pageId="10" pageNumber="295">Descriptive notes.</emphasis>
Head-body 9.5-10.5 cm, tail 7.5-8.5 cm; weight 25-45 g (males) and 20-40 g (females). There is slight sexual dimorphism for size. Fur color of the Fat-tailed Pseudantechinus is grayish-brown above with chestnut patches behind ears; belly is grayish-white. Tail is tapering, usually very fat at base and distinctly shorter than head-body length, and accessory erectile tissue of males forms an appendage to the penis. This combination of characteristics serves to distinguish the Fat-tailed Pseudantechinus from all congeners except Rory’s Pseudantechinus (PF. rory:), to which the Fat-tailed Pseudantechinus is very similar.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="2AC3655CFFA3244EFAC3F9FC07440733" pageId="10" pageNumber="295" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph id="626636D7FFA3244EFAC3F9FC07440733" blockId="10.[1375,2584,722,3475]" pageId="10" pageNumber="295">
<emphasis id="50ADEAC5FFA3244EFAC3F9FC0A87074A" bold="true" box="[1376,1487,1549,1582]" pageId="10" pageNumber="295">Habitat.</emphasis>
Mainly rocky hills and breakaways but also red sand plains (such as the Tanami Desert) where it nests inside termite mounds.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="2AC3655CFFA3244EFAC3F9AD07C5094B" pageId="10" pageNumber="295" type="food_feeding">
<paragraph id="626636D7FFA3244EFAC3F9AD07C5094B" blockId="10.[1375,2584,722,3475]" pageId="10" pageNumber="295">
<emphasis id="50ADEAC5FFA3244EFAC3F9AD09200719" bold="true" box="[1376,1640,1628,1661]" pageId="10" pageNumber="295">Food and Feeding.</emphasis>
Generally speaking, insects form the main component of the diet of the Fat-tailed Pseudantechinus, but spiders,slaters (Isopoda), snails (Pulmonata), and even rodents may be eaten. Tail becomes very fat when food is plentiful. Ten insect orders and spiders (
<taxonomicName id="A5D94D54FFA3244EF926F92309B40797" box="[1669,1788,1746,1779]" class="Pilidiophora" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="10" pageNumber="295" phylum="Nemertea" rank="order">Araneae</taxonomicName>
) were recorded in fecal samples from a population in West MacDonnell National Park, Northern Territory, during a 30month study; Isoptera, 
<taxonomicName id="A5D94D54FFA3244EFA04F8D0090D0626" box="[1447,1605,1825,1858]" class="Insecta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="295" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="order">Coleoptera</taxonomicName>
, and Orthoptera were the major insect ordersin the diet. A later study at the same site found some differences in prey items; there were three new classes and two new phyla in feces, including slaters, snails, and rodents. Specific identification of rodent hair in feces of Fat-tailed Pseudantechinuses was not possible, but the Central Australian Rock-rat (
<taxonomicName id="A5D94D54FFA3244EF957F84E075A0684" authorityName="Thomas" authorityYear="1909" box="[1780,2066,1983,2016]" class="Mammalia" family="Muridae" genus="Zyzomys" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="10" pageNumber="295" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="pedunculatus">Zyzomys pedunculatus</taxonomicName>
) was the common rodent at the site. Researchers speculated that the Fat-tailed Pseudantechinus might capture rodents or, given their small size, even feed on dead rodent carcasses.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="2AC3655CFFA3244EFAC2F7C4054B087F" pageId="10" pageNumber="295" type="breeding">
<paragraph id="626636D7FFA3244EFAC2F7C4054B087F" blockId="10.[1375,2584,722,3475]" pageId="10" pageNumber="295">
<emphasis id="50ADEAC5FFA3244EFAC2F7C40AAF0932" bold="true" box="[1377,1511,2101,2134]" pageId="10" pageNumber="295">Breeding.</emphasis>
The Fat-tailed Pseudantechinus is monoestrous, with a highly seasonal reproductive pattern. Births occurred in September—October in a population studied in the West MacDonnell National Park. Maximum litter size (and teat number) is six; young depend on their mother for c.14 weeks. Sexual maturity is reached in the first year, and both sexes breed in more than one year. The male has an appendage on the penis (similar to that of Rory’s Pseudantechinus), the function of which is unknown.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="2AC3655CFFA3244EFAFCF6D306500BC2" pageId="10" pageNumber="295" type="activity">
<paragraph id="626636D7FFA3244EFAFCF6D306500BC2" blockId="10.[1375,2584,722,3475]" pageId="10" pageNumber="295">
<emphasis id="50ADEAC5FFA3244EFAFCF6D309040827" bold="true" box="[1375,1612,2338,2371]" pageId="10" pageNumber="295">Activity patterns.</emphasis>
The Fat-tailed Pseudantechinus is predominantly nocturnal, but individuals are known to emerge from shelter among rocks to sun-bathe; indeed, Aborigines on occasion take advantage ofthis habit to catch them. One study assessed basking of the Fat-tailed Pseudantechinus in winter and found that they regularly foraged diurnally. Foraging bouts occurred throughout the day, but most bouts were observed within three hours of sunset. In comparison, basking occurred much more frequently in the morning. Basking and a shift toward diurnal foraging in winter were associated with a decrease in richness and abundance of predators. The Fat-tailed Pseudantechinus appears to compensate for occurrence of torpor on winter nights by changing its activity patterns and foraging during what is typically the rest phase.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="2AC3655CFFA3244EFAC1F55D065C0D6C" pageId="10" pageNumber="295" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph id="626636D7FFA3244EFAC1F55D065C0D6C" blockId="10.[1375,2584,722,3475]" pageId="10" pageNumber="295">
<emphasis id="50ADEAC5FFA3244EFAC1F55D076C0BA9" bold="true" box="[1378,2084,2732,2765]" pageId="10" pageNumber="295">Movements, Home range and Social organization.</emphasis>
One study conducted at Ormiston Creek (Central Australia) found that male Fat-tailed Pseudantechinuses occupied larger home ranges (0-98-1-5 ha) than females (0-31-0-43 ha). Home ranges overlapped little within a sex, but home ranges of males overlapped those of females by on average 38%. Anotherstudy at the samesite showed home range sizes that were 15-5-24-5 times larger than the previous study, but home range lengths of individuals were similar. The Fat-tailed Pseudantechinus appears to undergo fewer long-range movements than might be expected for an arid-zone dasyurid. This may be due to relatively high, stable resources (such as insect prey) in their favored rocky habitat.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="2AC3655CFFA3244EFAC0F3FF07300D90" pageId="10" pageNumber="295" type="conservation">
<paragraph id="626636D7FFA3244EFAC0F3FF07300D90" blockId="10.[1375,2584,722,3475]" pageId="10" pageNumber="295">
<emphasis id="50ADEAC5FFA3244EFAC0F3FF098C0D4B" bold="true" box="[1379,1732,3086,3119]" pageId="10" pageNumber="295">Status and Conservation.</emphasis>
Classified as Least Concern on The IUCN Red List. The Fattailed Pseudantechinus has a wide distribution and presumably a large overall population, and it occurs in a number of protected areas. It does not face any current major conservation threats. Habitats where the Fat-tailed Pseudantechinus occurs are rugged and not affected by European Rabbits (Oryctolagus cuniculus) or pastoralism. Domestic and feral cats may be a threat to some local populations.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
